    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about muscle growth and saw two different terms: mechanical tension and metabolic stress. can you explain the difference between them and which one is actually more important for hypertrophy?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Mechanical tension and metabolic stress are two key drivers of muscle growth, but they represent different aspects of the training stimulus. Mechanical tension is the physical force put on the muscle fibers, essentially the load you lift, which causes micro-tears. Metabolic stress is the buildup of metabolic byproducts like lactate within the muscle during intense, often high-rep, work. While both are important, many studies suggest that high mechanical tension is the primary driver for maximal hypertrophy.",
      "source": "target",
