    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if tension is the main driver, how does that actually work on a cellular level? like what's physically happening to the muscle fibers when they're under that load?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When muscle fibers are subjected to high mechanical tension, the stress is transmitted through the cytoskeleton, which is the internal scaffolding of the muscle cell. This tension activates various mechanosensors, which are proteins that detect the physical strain. These sensors then signal to the cell nucleus, triggering signaling pathways like the mTOR pathway, which ultimately promotes muscle protein synthesis—the process of building new muscle tissue.",
      "source": "target",
